00:00:17.180 --> 00:00:20.660
overall community over the last little bit more than a year.

00:00:20.670 --> 00:00:25.540
And I'm really excited about the possibilities that AtProto

00:00:25.700 --> 00:00:31.050
has for providing us agency over our social experience, over the

00:00:31.050 --> 00:00:34.970
way that we are able to shape our own science, our

00:00:35.100 --> 00:00:40.530
own investigation, and our own collective sensemaking, as I

00:00:40.590 --> 00:00:43.780
'm sure was talked about a lot at the AtScience

00:00:43.780 --> 00:00:47.040
meeting before the main meeting for this.

00:00:47.050 --> 00:00:50.700
So I'm going to talk about what we're building at

00:00:50.700 --> 00:00:55.060
Forecast to facilitate this vision of a future of AI built

00:00:55.140 --> 00:00:59.310
on AtProto using the tools that are available built into

00:00:59.550 --> 00:01:05.640
the infrastructure for the protocol to be able to facilitate collective sharing

00:01:05.640 --> 00:01:10.230
and understanding of data sets, large data sets, and also

00:01:10.230 --> 00:01:12.140
of model weights.

00:01:13.410 --> 00:01:18.540
So first, an introduction to Forecast, because it's

00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:23.250
probably a little bit out of left field to have a .

00:01:23.250 --> 00:01:27.310
bio domain show up at this setting, and not in

00:01:27.310 --> 00:01:30.290
the context of biographic, but actually biology.

00:01:30.370 --> 00:01:36.720
So Forecast is a drug discovery and development company, actually

00:01:36.720 --> 00:01:37.120
.

00:01:37.130 --> 00:01:41.820
And so our vision is really focused around providing people with cognitive

00:01:41.820 --> 00:01:45.970
agency and recognizing that historically we've done a very bad job

00:01:46.080 --> 00:01:51.420
of developing central nervous system therapeutics in the pharmaceutical space.

00:01:51.830 --> 00:01:54.940
So what we want to do is to say, look,

00:01:54.960 --> 00:01:59.440
there is this vast space of where your mind could be at

00:01:59.440 --> 00:02:03.440
any given moment, and a vast way in which your mind

00:02:03.440 --> 00:02:07.370
can evolve in its instantaneous state across this space of all the

00:02:07.370 --> 00:02:09.640
different things that a mind can be.

00:02:09.910 --> 00:02:12.560
So you're somewhere in this vast sea of all the potential

00:02:12.560 --> 00:02:14.240
mental states that are possible.

00:02:14.350 --> 00:02:17.640
And what we want to do is to be able to produce

00:02:17.640 --> 00:02:20.240
therapeutic interventions.

00:02:20.250 --> 00:02:23.420
We're starting with drugs, with small molecule drugs, but

00:02:23.450 --> 00:02:26.110
we'd really like to see this expand into all types of

00:02:26.110 --> 00:02:30.420
different interventions that allow you to say, okay, no matter

00:02:30.420 --> 00:02:33.290
which spot that you're at in this space, I want

00:02:33.290 --> 00:02:36.560
to be able to move to any other spot in this space

00:02:36.810 --> 00:02:40.880
to give you control of the way that your mind operates over

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:41.660
time.

00:02:41.670 --> 00:02:47.170
And so we think that this overall vision provides a really different

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:52.290
way of thinking about how drugs are developed in neurology and

00:02:52.360 --> 00:02:55.730
psychiatry, where historically we've had a really difficult time

00:02:55.730 --> 00:02:57.000
bringing new tools to market.

00:02:58.010 --> 00:03:01.700
And so we are using artificial intelligence models, both on the

00:03:01.950 --> 00:03:04.930
language side, on the image side, on the multimod

00:03:04.930 --> 00:03:07.980
al side, all of these different techniques that have really been

00:03:08.100 --> 00:03:13.890
radically transformative in every field of science and computation over the last

00:03:13.950 --> 00:03:16.290
few years, to be able to build out this map of

00:03:16.290 --> 00:03:19.380
every cognitive state that a person can be in over time,

00:03:19.690 --> 00:03:23.690
and then to understand the biology by growing many brains in the

00:03:23.690 --> 00:03:28.980
lab and then watching the videos of their brain activity over time

00:03:29.200 --> 00:03:32.960
to be able to map out how pharmaceutical interventions impact these things

00:03:32.970 --> 00:03:33.160
.

00:03:34.950 --> 00:03:38.570
So the difficulty that we run into with this is that right

00:03:38.570 --> 00:03:43.430
now in the ecosystem for AI, these models are really largely

00:03:43.430 --> 00:03:47.220
produced from a small subset of orgs, as I'm

00:03:47.220 --> 00:03:50.100
sure a lot of people in the audience are familiar with from

00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:50.500
this.

00:03:50.550 --> 00:03:54.240
And this provides really a number of practical and, I think

00:03:54.490 --> 00:03:57.840
, for the field, for science as a whole, existential

00:03:57.840 --> 00:04:00.580
problems that come from, like, what are the long-

00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:05.000
term impacts of having, like, the incentive structures that are

00:04:05.010 --> 00:04:08.080
present for individual large orgs producing these models, the way

00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:11.380
that even just having any concentration of only a small, sp

00:04:11.630 --> 00:04:15.300
arse subset of models makes people anchor their understanding.

00:04:15.310 --> 00:04:17.160
So even, you know, like, if you have a

00:04:17.160 --> 00:04:20.160
large number of individual startups that are sort of, like,

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:22.880
building things based off of these, like, say, in

00:04:22.890 --> 00:04:25.180
the biotech space, if you have image models that

00:04:25.260 --> 00:04:27.980
show you biological imaging, that they're all based off of

00:04:28.080 --> 00:04:30.000
the same sort of, like, underlying base.

00:04:30.010 --> 00:04:32.460
And, like, the knowledge that you're seeing, actually

00:04:32.460 --> 00:04:35.580
, when you're doing scientific investigation, is really, really

00:04:35.970 --> 00:04:38.930
concentrated around whatever was the semantics that was put into the

00:04:38.930 --> 00:04:41.260
specific training regime of that, right?

00:04:41.270 --> 00:04:44.270
So there's this outsized power that comes in being able

00:04:44.270 --> 00:04:46.770
to, like, be the one that controls that.

00:04:46.850 --> 00:04:49.100
And there's also, like, an outsized effect of

00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:52.030
, like, sort of quashing the variability in the entire

00:04:52.030 --> 00:04:54.200
ecosystem of the way investigation works.

00:04:54.210 --> 00:04:56.130
And this is something that, actually, a lot of people

00:04:56.130 --> 00:04:58.840
, like, Anthropic has even published on the overall effect

00:04:58.840 --> 00:05:02.100
of this for language models and the way that we interact with

00:05:02.100 --> 00:05:04.180
text and the language that we produce.

00:05:04.230 --> 00:05:07.180
So this really, this concentration of, like, the training

00:05:07.180 --> 00:05:10.420
, the infrastructure into only a handful of players is really,

00:05:10.420 --> 00:05:13.440
really deleterious for the field overall long-term.

00:05:15.090 --> 00:05:21.060
But AppRoto is this incredible ecosystem that provides this infrastructure

00:05:21.060 --> 00:05:24.670
for solving, really, this exact problem of being able to

00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:28.950
have, like, data that is distributed, that people have

00:05:28.950 --> 00:05:31.440
ownership, real, genuine ownership.

00:05:31.450 --> 00:05:34.920
It's not locked into, like, a particular monolithic

00:05:34.920 --> 00:05:38.900
, like, space that is, like, schematized

00:05:38.910 --> 00:05:41.920
in order to be, like, mutually understandable and exchangeable

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:45.080
, which is something that, for scientific data, is something

00:05:45.080 --> 00:05:46.500
that's incredibly important.

00:05:46.510 --> 00:05:49.520
Like, an image is not the same as any other image

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:49.840
.

00:05:49.850 --> 00:05:52.360
Like, the actual experimental detail really matter.

00:05:52.370 --> 00:05:54.520
And so being able to, like, bookkeep on that

00:05:54.520 --> 00:05:56.040
is incredibly important.

00:05:56.050 --> 00:05:58.760
Identity is incredibly important in this context.

00:05:58.770 --> 00:06:01.520
Like, being able to understand where data is coming from in

00:06:01.520 --> 00:06:03.510
such a way that, like, doesn't lead to the

00:06:03.510 --> 00:06:06.760
same concentrating effects, but allows people to, like, like

00:06:06.760 --> 00:06:08.990
, contribute, but in a way that is, like,

00:06:08.990 --> 00:06:10.140
trust is built out.

00:06:10.150 --> 00:06:12.630
Like, it's currently done in the Blue Sky ecosystem with

00:06:12.630 --> 00:06:15.060
, like, verifications, and the verification graph kind of

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:16.480
architecture that's there.

00:06:16.570 --> 00:06:19.670
And then, like, building out in a way that's

00:06:19.680 --> 00:06:22.840
composable, that actually has, like, open protocols that

00:06:22.840 --> 00:06:24.440
allow applications to interchange.

00:06:25.190 --> 00:06:28.210
And so, like, this has already been really started to

00:06:28.280 --> 00:06:33.320
flourish amazingly on the side for social, but for scientific data

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:35.340
, I think that people were talking about on sort of,

00:06:35.370 --> 00:06:38.720
like, the knowledge side at the at science meeting, like

00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:40.340
, is really starting to blossom.

00:06:40.430 --> 00:06:43.450
And I think that there is an incredible opportunity even outside of

00:06:43.520 --> 00:06:46.450
, like, the social and sort of, like, direct

00:06:46.450 --> 00:06:50.060
text knowledge side to actually how we share interoperable,

00:06:50.170 --> 00:06:51.500
just full-on data sets.

00:06:51.590 --> 00:06:54.840
So, what we're building is based off of this model

00:06:54.840 --> 00:06:58.540
, that, like, positive sum is really important for providing

00:06:58.650 --> 00:07:01.720
a meaningful way for small orgs like our startup, like

00:07:01.720 --> 00:07:04.480
other biotech startups, to, like, meaningfully

00:07:04.660 --> 00:07:07.710
be able to produce AI models that compete with the large labs

00:07:07.710 --> 00:07:07.900
.

00:07:07.910 --> 00:07:11.390
Like, this happens because of coordination between everybody in the field

00:07:11.390 --> 00:07:14.640
, us sharing data, others sharing data, us sharing weights

00:07:14.640 --> 00:07:16.730
, others sharing weights that's done in a way that's

00:07:16.730 --> 00:07:18.920
, like, interoperable, so that the sum total

00:07:19.050 --> 00:07:22.290
of all of our small startups in the ecosystem is something that

00:07:22.290 --> 00:07:24.210
's greater than the sum of its parts.

00:07:24.230 --> 00:07:25.820
And so, this is, like, what we see is

00:07:25.820 --> 00:07:28.720
really, like, a path forward built off of the infrastructure

00:07:28.900 --> 00:07:30.980
for AppRoto for, like, a small 10-

00:07:31.270 --> 00:07:33.200
person team, say, to be able to, like,

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:35.430
out-compete massive organizations.

00:07:35.450 --> 00:07:40.310
And that's because the network, the infrastructure, is the

00:07:40.310 --> 00:07:44.400
force multiplier for our efforts in training, like, building robust

00:07:44.580 --> 00:07:45.260
AI systems.

00:07:46.450 --> 00:07:48.890
And so, what we've built at Forecast over the

00:07:48.890 --> 00:07:54.540
last bit is our own paths that really, like, treating

00:07:54.540 --> 00:07:55.660
this for data sets.

00:07:55.690 --> 00:07:57.440
We found this to be something that's, like, really

00:07:57.440 --> 00:08:00.360
important for our own infrastructure, for how we're building our

00:08:00.360 --> 00:08:03.370
, like, image models, video models, like, multim

00:08:03.560 --> 00:08:08.460
odal models that we're using internally for our own discovery

00:08:08.460 --> 00:08:09.540
and development programs.

00:08:10.230 --> 00:08:12.850
And so, what we're, like, we decided to

00:08:12.850 --> 00:08:15.780
really try and put some work into making that generalizable so

00:08:15.780 --> 00:08:18.160
that we can share it with the community and have this larger

00:08:18.340 --> 00:08:19.780
buy-in around sharing data.

00:08:19.790 --> 00:08:23.480
So, what AppData is really based on is the

00:08:23.730 --> 00:08:27.110
fundamental technology called the web data set, which is a way

00:08:27.110 --> 00:08:30.760
that, like, individual large data sets can be, like

00:08:30.760 --> 00:08:31.780
, sharded up.

00:08:31.790 --> 00:08:32.380
It's very simple.

00:08:32.390 --> 00:08:33.770
It's just, like, tar files, essentially.

00:08:34.070 --> 00:08:35.970
They could, like, put into, like, shards

00:08:35.970 --> 00:08:36.200
.

00:08:36.210 --> 00:08:39.760
But because of the wrapper that you can sort of do on

00:08:39.760 --> 00:08:42.170
top of that, it provides a really good, like,

00:08:42.360 --> 00:08:46.030
you can schematize things very easily by having a standardized

00:08:46.030 --> 00:08:48.340
way that those files are stored, and you can stream things

00:08:48.630 --> 00:08:51.650
really easily and have, like, sidecar manifest files that

00:08:51.650 --> 00:08:53.450
let you do, like, querying and other operations really

00:08:53.450 --> 00:08:53.920
quickly.

00:08:54.250 --> 00:08:55.640
So, we're trying to, like, build out,

00:08:55.820 --> 00:08:59.760
essentially, an ecosystem in which there is storage infrastructure for the

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:02.360
actual large data sets itself that's off-protocol.

00:09:02.370 --> 00:09:04.870
As, like, a funny thing, I kind of built

00:09:04.870 --> 00:09:06.800
, like, a version of it that does work for PD

00:09:06.800 --> 00:09:07.380
S blobs.

00:09:07.390 --> 00:09:08.770
But, like, so, like, I think I have

00:09:08.960 --> 00:09:10.960
, like, a few versions of, like, MN

00:09:10.960 --> 00:09:12.900
IST tested as, like, PDS blobs on my

00:09:12.900 --> 00:09:14.050
own, like, maxine.

00:09:14.050 --> 00:09:14.580
science.

00:09:14.590 --> 00:09:19.370
And then we use AppProto PDS records to actually

00:09:19.370 --> 00:09:23.140
be, like, the index, the metadata, the schem

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:25.900
as that give, like, the interpretation of what each individual

00:09:25.900 --> 00:09:30.240
sample is in a given data set, and then lens transformations

00:09:30.250 --> 00:09:33.390
that allow you to actually move back and forth between schemat

00:09:33.860 --> 00:09:35.200
izations of individual samples.

00:09:35.210 --> 00:09:38.040
So, you can aggregate across data sets that are actually made

00:09:38.050 --> 00:09:40.660
with, like, different sample schemas, but that are

00:09:40.660 --> 00:09:41.540
interconvertible.

00:09:42.190 --> 00:09:45.710
And so, we're, like, still, we have

00:09:45.710 --> 00:09:48.360
a version of this that's up on PyPI.

00:09:48.370 --> 00:09:51.310
I'm pushing the REST SDK for this right now today

00:09:51.310 --> 00:09:51.620
.

00:09:51.630 --> 00:09:53.010
Thank you, Claude.

00:09:53.170 --> 00:09:56.100
But we're really, really excited to get, like,

00:09:56.100 --> 00:09:58.080
community feedback and sort of, like, iterate on the way

00:09:58.100 --> 00:09:59.060
that we've designed this.

00:09:59.070 --> 00:10:02.450
So, as I was mentioning, like, the design of

00:10:02.450 --> 00:10:06.320
this overall is that, like, really is centrally done

00:10:06.320 --> 00:10:07.480
through code.

00:10:07.490 --> 00:10:09.970
Like, it's, I think, different than a lot

00:10:09.970 --> 00:10:11.820
of things that we see in, like, the app proto

00:10:11.930 --> 00:10:13.950
ecosystem and that there's really no, like, I mean

00:10:13.950 --> 00:10:16.910
, I think over time, it'll be nice to have

00:10:16.910 --> 00:10:19.380
, like, a web front end to allow people to browse

00:10:19.380 --> 00:10:20.640
data sets and things like that.

00:10:20.650 --> 00:10:22.400
But really, this is something that, like, we've

00:10:22.400 --> 00:10:25.610
envisioned as being something that you reference and, like, your

00:10:25.610 --> 00:10:27.740
own Jupyter Notebooks are doing data science and something

00:10:27.920 --> 00:10:31.420
that you have your autonomous, like, agents on cloud code

00:10:31.430 --> 00:10:33.530
or whatever, on codex or what have you, actually

00:10:33.530 --> 00:10:36.740
be able to just, like, build things that, like

00:10:36.920 --> 00:10:40.360
, query out to our, like, app view that's

00:10:40.360 --> 00:10:42.860
aggregating all of the data sets that are posted in all

00:10:42.860 --> 00:10:43.860
the different fields.

00:10:43.870 --> 00:10:47.560
Genomics, like, neural recordings of, you know,

00:10:47.570 --> 00:10:51.010
voltage dynamics and neurons, like, imaging data sets for medical

00:10:51.010 --> 00:10:54.340
imaging, for biological imaging, all these different things that can

00:10:54.340 --> 00:10:59.040
be posted, have entries as, like, PDS records

00:10:59.040 --> 00:11:01.790
that give, like, the metadata of the data set and

00:11:01.790 --> 00:11:03.040
what schema it's using.

00:11:03.210 --> 00:11:06.380
All of that be, like, aggregated and filtered in

00:11:06.380 --> 00:11:09.220
real time in order to provide, like, people who are

00:11:09.220 --> 00:11:12.030
working on different data, like, fields with, like,

00:11:12.070 --> 00:11:15.100
real-time streams of when new data gets posted out.

00:11:15.110 --> 00:11:18.140
And then specifically, like, having, like, we're

00:11:18.140 --> 00:11:23.240
building out a very similar, like, trust network architecture that

00:11:23.240 --> 00:11:25.580
was inspired, really, by the Blue Sky Verification System

00:11:25.590 --> 00:11:27.550
to have it so that there can be, like, in

00:11:27.550 --> 00:11:31.130
a given field, like, trust labels that are given to

00:11:31.650 --> 00:11:34.240
individual data providers that allow people to, like, actually hone

00:11:34.240 --> 00:11:36.600
in on that data that's being provided by really, really

00:11:36.930 --> 00:11:38.780
reliable sources for particular fields.

00:11:38.790 --> 00:11:44.210
And then when individual clients look out to what's present in

00:11:44.210 --> 00:11:46.710
the atmosphere as far as the records, like, give the

00:11:46.710 --> 00:11:48.960
index on, like, all the data that's present out

00:11:48.960 --> 00:11:51.750
in the world, then the client has all the information that

00:11:51.750 --> 00:11:54.490
it needs to actually then go out to the storage mechanism and

00:11:54.490 --> 00:11:57.720
actually, like, pull the streaming samples for that data.

00:11:57.930 --> 00:11:59.890
And we also, the arrow's not depicted here, but

00:11:59.890 --> 00:12:02.520
we can, like, proxy that connection through the app view

00:12:02.520 --> 00:12:02.860
also.

00:12:02.870 --> 00:12:04.270
There's, like, a lot of different ways that we

00:12:04.270 --> 00:12:05.460
can plug all of these things together.

00:12:05.530 --> 00:12:08.210
But this is the overall vision, is, like, the

00:12:08.210 --> 00:12:10.940
client is able to look out into the entire atmosphere and say

00:12:11.120 --> 00:12:18.980
, what has science done in, like, mouse brain MRI

00:12:18.980 --> 00:12:19.920
or something?

00:12:20.190 --> 00:12:21.260
Like, whatever it is.

00:12:21.270 --> 00:12:25.030
And, like, any data set that has a lens that

00:12:25.030 --> 00:12:28.600
lets you convert it to something that I can interpret as mouse

00:12:28.600 --> 00:12:34.120
brain MRI, I see index records from the atmosphere that tell

00:12:34.120 --> 00:12:36.040
me where to look for all of those data sets.

00:12:36.050 --> 00:12:39.180
And that let me code gen, like, transformations from my

00:12:39.360 --> 00:12:41.790
own data science pipeline that let me ingest all of it

00:12:41.980 --> 00:12:44.480
streaming from out in the larger, like, web.

00:12:45.770 --> 00:12:47.830
So we've built all of this off of, as I

00:12:47.830 --> 00:12:50.250
mentioned, sort of, like, not, like, Lex

